CC  Urate is the product of xanthine catabolism by either the xanthine
CC  dehydrogenase complex (GenProp0640) or xanthine oxidase. The purine
CC  ring system of urate is oxidized by uricase (urate oxidase) and the
CC  6-membered ring is opened by hydroxyisourate hydrolase. The hydrolase
CC  may be unnecessary in some organisms as the hydroxyisourate will
CC  hydrolyze spontaneously, albeit an a slow rate. The resulting product
CC  (OHCU) then spontaneously decarboxylates, resulting in a mixture of
CC  (S)- and (R)-allantoin. For further catabolism, generally only
CC  (S)-allantoin is processed, so allantoin racemace is also typically
CC  found.  An OHCU carboxylase has been discovered in Mus musculus which
CC  does have homologs in prokaryotes.
